 "components": {
  "instruction": "You are given a short free-text user utterance as input, which represents a brief user request, command, or question. Your goal is to classify the user’s intention behind each input into exactly one category, chosen from a specific set of predefined intent labels.\n\n**Input Format:**  \n- Each input contains a single field named 'text', comprised of a user utterance (for example: \"repeat alarm\" or \"what's happening today\").\n\n**Output Requirements:**  \n- Output only the most accurate single category label from the list provided below for each input.\n- Do not output any explanations, reasoning, extra text, or multiple labels—only the one category that best fits the user’s intent.\n\n**Category List:**  \n- alarm_query\n- alarm_set\n- calendar_query\n- calendar_remove\n- calendar_set\n- cooking_recipe\n- datetime_query\n- email_query\n- email_sendemail\n- general_quirky\n- iot_hue_lightoff\n- lists_createoradd\n- lists_query\n- lists_remove\n- music_query\n- news_query\n- play_audiobook\n- play_music\n- play_podcasts\n- play_radio\n- qa_currency\n- qa_definition\n- qa_factoid\n- qa_stock\n- recommendation_events\n- recommendation_locations\n- social_post\n- takeaway_order\n- transport_query\n- weather_query\n\n**Guidance and Domain-Specific Rules:**  \n1. Read the 'text' carefully to determine the specific intent, not just the high-level topic.\n2. Always select only one label per input, even if several could be loosely applicable.\n3. Apply the following domain-specific disambiguation rules closely:\n    - **Alarm:**  \n        - Select 'alarm_set' for any request to set, change, or modify an alarm (including commands like \"repeat alarm\", \"set alarm\", \"change alarm\").\n        - Select 'alarm_query' for requests that ask for information about alarms (such as \"what alarms do I have?\", \"when is my next alarm?\").\n    - **Lists:**  \n        - Use 'lists_createoradd' for creating new lists or adding items.\n        - Use 'lists_query' when asking about the contents of a list.\n        - Use 'lists_remove' for removing/deleting items from lists.\n    - **Music and Media:**  \n        - Use 'music_query' to request information about music or song recommendations.\n        - Use 'play_music' when the user wants music to be played.\n    - **Recommendations:**  \n        - Use 'recommendation_locations' for requests about where to go, such as suggestions for restaurants or places.\n        - 'recommendation_events' for suggestions about things to do (activities, events).\n        - Do NOT use these for requests about how to get somewhere or travel details—see 'transport_query' below.\n    - **Transport:**  \n        - Use 'transport_query' for requests related to navigation, directions, travel routes, or transport schedules (\"how do I get to…\", \"what's the next train to…\").\n    - **General Knowledge and Facts:**  \n        - Use 'qa_factoid' for straightforward factual questions (e.g., \"Who is the president of France?\", \"When did WW2 end?\").\n        - Use 'qa_definition' for questions seeking the meaning or definition of a word or phrase (\"What does ephemeral mean?\").\n    - **General or Chat:**  \n        - Use 'general_quirky' only for open-ended, fun, trivia, entertainment, non-task-oriented, or conversational responses (e.g., jokes, general small talk, movie plots, etc.).\n    - **Calendar:**  \n        - Use 'calendar_query' for requests for information about events or availability on the calendar.\n        - Use 'calendar_set' for creating or adding a new event.\n        - Use 'calendar_remove' for requests to remove or delete a calendar event.\n    - **News and Weather:**  \n        - Use 'news_query' for requests about current events and news (“what’s happening today”, “news update”).\n        - Use 'weather_query' for weather-related questions (“Is it going to rain?”).\n    - **Datetime:**  \n        - Use 'datetime_query' for questions about the date or current time.\n    - **Email:**  \n        - Use 'email_query' for requests to check or search email.\n        - Use 'email_sendemail' for composing or sending emails.\n    - **Other:**  \n        - Assign the most specific category if there is overlap between categories.\n        - Use 'qa_currency' for currency conversion or exchange rate queries.\n        - Use 'qa_stock' for questions about stock prices or financial markets.\n\n4. Be attentive to subtle intent cues in inputs that could change the label (e.g., task-oriented versus open-ended queries).\n5. When intent is ambiguous, apply the most precise domain rule above to resolve.\n6. If the utterance is about news or current events (e.g., \"what's happening today\"), use 'news_query', not 'calendar_query' or 'general_quirky'.\n7. Never output anything except one category label from the list.\n\n**Summary:**  \nFor every provided 'text' input, analyze the intent using the above domain guidance and output exactly one matching label from the provided list—nothing else."
 },
